{
  "What is the fuel most commonly used in nuclear power plants?": "",
  "Plutonium-239": "",
  "Hydrogen-2 (deuterium)": "",
  "Thorium-232": "",
  "Uranium-235": "",
  "Uranium-235 is the most commonly used fuel in nuclear power plants. It is the only naturally occurring isotope that is fissile, meaning it can sustain a nuclear chain reaction when bombarded with neutrons.": "",
  "In a nuclear fission reaction, what happens to the nucleus of a heavy atom?": "",
  "It splits into two or more smaller nuclei, releasing energy": "",
  "It combines with another nucleus to form a larger atom": "",
  "It loses all its electrons but the nucleus stays intact": "",
  "It absorbs light and becomes heavier": "",
  "In nuclear fission, the nucleus of a heavy atom such as uranium-235 absorbs a neutron and splits into two or more smaller nuclei (fission products), along with additional neutrons and a large amount of energy. This splitting is the fundamental process that powers nuclear reactors.": "",
  "What role do control rods play in a nuclear reactor?": "",
  "They generate the initial neutrons to start the reaction": "",
  "They cool the reactor core with water": "",
  "They absorb excess neutrons to regulate the rate of the chain reaction": "",
  "They convert heat into electricity": "",
  "Control rods are made of neutron-absorbing materials such as boron, cadmium, or hafnium. By inserting or withdrawing the control rods from the reactor core, operators can absorb more or fewer neutrons, thereby regulating the rate of the fission chain reaction and controlling the reactor's power output.": "",
  "What type of nuclear reaction powers the Sun?": "",
  "Nuclear fission": "",
  "Nuclear fusion": "",
  "Radioactive decay": "",
  "Chemical combustion": "",
  "The Sun is powered by nuclear fusion, in which hydrogen nuclei combine under extreme temperature and pressure to form helium, releasing enormous amounts of energy in the process. The Sun's core reaches temperatures of about 15 million degrees Celsius, providing the conditions necessary for fusion.": "",
  "What is the primary advantage of nuclear power compared to fossil fuels in terms of emissions?": "",
  "Nuclear fuel is cheaper than coal": "",
  "Nuclear power produces no radioactive waste": "",
  "Nuclear power plants emit no greenhouse gases during electricity generation": "",
  "Nuclear reactors can be built anywhere without safety concerns": "",
  "Nuclear power plants produce virtually no greenhouse gas emissions during electricity generation, unlike coal and natural gas plants which release large quantities of CO2. While the mining of uranium and plant construction have some associated emissions, the operational carbon footprint is extremely low.": "",
  "What is the main challenge preventing nuclear fusion from being used as a commercial energy source?": "",
  "There is no hydrogen available on Earth for fusion fuel": "",
  "Scientists have not yet discovered which elements can undergo fusion": "",
  "Fusion reactions do not produce any energy": "",
  "Achieving and sustaining the extremely high temperatures and pressures needed for a controlled fusion reaction": "",
  "The primary challenge of nuclear fusion is achieving and maintaining the extreme conditions required: temperatures exceeding 100 million degrees Celsius and sufficient plasma confinement. At these temperatures, matter exists as plasma, which is extremely difficult to contain. No material container can withstand such temperatures, requiring magnetic or inertial confinement approaches.": "",
  "What happens in a nuclear chain reaction?": "",
  "Electrons jump from one atom to the next in sequence": "",
  "Radioactive atoms spontaneously arrange themselves in a line": "",
  "One fission event releases neutrons that trigger additional fission events in a self-sustaining process": "",
  "Atoms are linked together in a chain formation": "",
  "In a nuclear chain reaction, each fission event produces additional neutrons that can trigger further fission events in nearby fuel atoms. If at least one neutron from each fission causes another fission, the reaction becomes self-sustaining. Nuclear reactors are designed to maintain a controlled chain reaction.": "",
  "What type of radiation is a major concern in the storage of spent nuclear fuel?": "",
  "Radio waves": "",
  "Infrared radiation only": "",
  "Visible light": "",
  "Gamma radiation and other ionizing radiation": "",
  "Spent nuclear fuel emits gamma radiation and other forms of ionizing radiation that are dangerous to living organisms. This high-energy radiation can penetrate materials and damage DNA, which is why spent fuel must be stored in heavily shielded containers and carefully managed for thousands of years.": "",
  "Approximately what percentage of the world's electricity is generated by nuclear power?": "",
  "About 75%": "",
  "About 50%": "",
  "About 10%": "",
  "About 1%": "",
  "Nuclear power generates approximately 10% of the world's electricity, with about 440 commercial nuclear reactors operating in over 30 countries. France has the highest nuclear share of any major country, generating about 70% of its electricity from nuclear power.": "",
  "What is the purpose of the containment structure surrounding a nuclear reactor?": "",
  "To prevent the release of radioactive materials into the environment in case of an accident": "",
  "To make the reactor look more imposing": "",
  "To increase the efficiency of the nuclear reaction": "",
  "To cool the reactor by allowing air circulation": "",
  "The containment structure is a massive, reinforced concrete and steel dome designed to contain radioactive materials in the event of a reactor accident. It serves as the last barrier between the radioactive core and the environment, withstanding high pressures and temperatures that might occur during an emergency.": "",
  "What is nuclear fission?": "",
  "The process of combining two light atomic nuclei to form a heavier nucleus": "",
  "The absorption of neutrons without any energy release": "",
  "The emission of electrons from an unstable atom": "",
  "The splitting of a heavy atomic nucleus into two or more lighter nuclei, accompanied by the release of energy": "",
  "Nuclear fission is the process in which a heavy atomic nucleus, such as uranium-235 or plutonium-239, splits into two or more lighter nuclei when struck by a neutron. This splitting releases a tremendous amount of energy, additional neutrons, and radiation, and is the principle behind nuclear power plants.": "",
  "What is nuclear fusion?": "",
  "The splitting of heavy atoms into lighter ones": "",
  "The combining of two light atomic nuclei to form a heavier nucleus, releasing energy": "",
  "The decay of radioactive isotopes over time": "",
  "The chemical bonding of nuclear fuel rods": "",
  "Nuclear fusion is the process in which two light atomic nuclei combine to form a heavier nucleus, releasing enormous amounts of energy. This is the reaction that powers stars, including our Sun, where hydrogen nuclei fuse to form helium under extreme temperature and pressure conditions.": "",
  "What is a nuclear meltdown?": "",
  "The normal shutdown procedure for a nuclear reactor": "",
  "A severe nuclear reactor accident in which the fuel rods overheat and the reactor core melts, potentially releasing radioactive materials": "",
  "The controlled melting of uranium ore during fuel processing": "",
  "The gradual cooling of spent nuclear fuel in storage pools": "",
  "A nuclear meltdown is a severe accident in which the cooling system of a nuclear reactor fails, causing the nuclear fuel rods to overheat and melt through their containment. This can release radioactive materials and is one of the most feared scenarios in nuclear energy, as occurred at Chernobyl in 1986 and Fukushima in 2011.": "",
  "What is radioactive waste?": "",
  "The steam released from cooling towers at nuclear plants": "",
  "Non-toxic byproducts of uranium mining that can be safely disposed of in landfills": "",
  "Any waste produced by a power plant, regardless of fuel type": "",
  "Waste material that contains radioactive isotopes and emits ionizing radiation, requiring special handling and long-term storage": "",
  "Radioactive waste is material containing radioactive isotopes that emit harmful ionizing radiation. It is generated by nuclear power plants, medical facilities, and research institutions. High-level waste from reactor fuel remains dangerously radioactive for thousands of years and must be securely stored in engineered containment facilities.": "",
  "What is a half-life in the context of nuclear science?": "",
  "The time it takes for a nuclear reactor to reach half of its operating temperature": "",
  "The period during which a nuclear power plant operates at half capacity": "",
  "The time required for half of the atoms in a radioactive sample to decay": "",
  "Half the expected operational lifespan of a nuclear reactor": "",
  "A half-life is the time required for half of the radioactive atoms in a sample to undergo radioactive decay. Each radioactive isotope has a characteristic half-life, ranging from fractions of a second to billions of years. For example, plutonium-239 has a half-life of about 24,000 years.": "",
  "What is enrichment in the context of nuclear fuel?": "",
  "Adding vitamins and minerals to uranium fuel pellets": "",
  "Mixing uranium with plutonium to increase energy output": "",
  "Coating fuel rods with a protective layer of lead": "",
  "The process of increasing the concentration of uranium-235 in a uranium sample above its natural abundance": "",
  "Uranium enrichment is the process of increasing the percentage of uranium-235 in a uranium sample. Natural uranium contains only about 0.7% U-235, but most nuclear reactors require fuel enriched to 3-5% U-235. Enrichment is typically performed using gas centrifuges that separate isotopes based on their slight mass differences.": "",
  "What is a coolant in a nuclear reactor?": "",
  "A substance that slows down neutrons to make fission more likely": "",
  "A fluid that absorbs heat from the reactor core and transfers it to generate steam for electricity production": "",
  "A chemical that neutralizes radioactivity in spent fuel": "",
  "A gas that prevents corrosion of fuel rods": "",
  "A coolant is a fluid, typically water, that circulates through the reactor core to absorb the intense heat generated by fission reactions. This heat is then used to produce steam, which drives turbines to generate electricity. Loss of coolant is one of the most serious emergencies that can occur in a nuclear reactor.": "",
  "What is a moderator in a nuclear reactor?": "",
  "A material that slows down fast neutrons so they are more likely to cause fission in uranium-235": "",
  "A material that absorbs neutrons to stop the chain reaction": "",
  "A device that measures radiation levels in the reactor": "",
  "A person who supervises reactor operations": "",
  "A moderator is a material used in nuclear reactors to slow down the fast neutrons produced by fission so that they are more likely to be absorbed by uranium-235 nuclei and cause further fission. Common moderators include ordinary water, heavy water, and graphite.": "",
  "What is a breeder reactor?": "",
  "A reactor designed to produce more fissile material than it consumes by converting fertile isotopes into fissile ones": "",
  "A small reactor used only for research purposes": "",
  "A reactor that generates electricity and desalinates water simultaneously": "",
  "A reactor that uses only recycled nuclear fuel": "",
  "A breeder reactor is a nuclear reactor designed to generate more fissile material than it consumes. It converts non-fissile (fertile) isotopes, such as uranium-238 or thorium-232, into fissile isotopes like plutonium-239 or uranium-233, effectively creating new nuclear fuel during operation.": "",
  "What is critical mass?": "",
  "The minimum amount of fissile material needed to sustain a nuclear chain reaction": "",
  "The total mass of all nuclear fuel loaded into a reactor": "",
  "The weight of a nuclear warhead": "",
  "The maximum weight a nuclear reactor containment building can support": "",
  "Critical mass is the minimum amount of fissile material needed to maintain a self-sustaining nuclear chain reaction. Below critical mass, too many neutrons escape from the surface of the material without causing further fission, and the chain reaction dies out. The exact critical mass depends on the shape, density, and purity of the material.": "",
  "After the 2011 Fukushima disaster in Japan, Germany announced plans to phase out all of its nuclear power plants by 2022. A German energy analyst argues that this decision could increase the country's carbon emissions. What is the most logical basis for this argument?": "",
  "Closing nuclear plants may require increased use of fossil fuels like coal and natural gas to meet electricity demand, thereby increasing CO2 emissions": "",
  "Nuclear power plants emit more carbon than coal plants": "",
  "Decommissioning nuclear plants requires burning large quantities of coal": "",
  "Nuclear waste storage releases large amounts of CO2": "",
  "When nuclear power plants are closed, the electricity they generated must be replaced by other sources. If renewable energy cannot fill the gap fast enough, fossil fuel plants like coal and natural gas must increase production, leading to higher carbon emissions. This trade-off between nuclear safety concerns and climate goals is a real dilemma faced by policymakers.": "",
  "A community lives near a proposed site for a deep geological repository for high-level nuclear waste. Residents are concerned about the safety of storing radioactive materials underground for thousands of years. Which of the following is the strongest scientific argument for the safety of deep geological storage?": "",
  "Underground temperatures will neutralize the radioactivity": "",
  "Radioactive waste loses all its radioactivity within 100 years": "",
  "Deep geological formations have been stable for millions of years, and engineered barriers plus the natural geology provide multiple layers of containment": "",
  "Groundwater will dilute the waste to safe levels immediately": "",
  "Deep geological repositories are designed using the concept of multiple barriers: engineered containers, buffer materials, and the surrounding stable rock formation itself. Geological formations hundreds of meters underground have remained stable for millions to billions of years, providing strong confidence that they can isolate waste for the thousands of years needed.": "",
  "Scientists at a fusion research facility achieve a breakthrough by producing more energy from a fusion reaction than was used to initiate it. A journalist asks why this cannot immediately be scaled up to a power plant. What is the most accurate response?": "",
  "Fusion reactions produce too little energy to be commercially useful following conventional understanding": "",
  "A single successful experiment does not solve the engineering challenges of sustaining continuous fusion reactions, managing extreme heat, and building materials that can withstand reactor conditions for years of operation": "",
  "Fusion energy has already been scaled up; the journalist is misinformed when considering all relevant factors": "",
  "Fusion power plants are illegal under international law, particularly regarding economically when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Moving from a laboratory demonstration to a commercial power plant requires solving immense engineering challenges including sustaining plasma at millions of degrees for extended periods, developing materials that can withstand intense neutron bombardment, managing tritium fuel cycles, and building economically viable reactor designs. These challenges may take decades to overcome.": "",
  "A small island nation with no fossil fuel resources is evaluating energy options. They have considered building a small modular nuclear reactor (SMR). A local environmental group opposes the plan, citing the Chernobyl disaster. How would a nuclear engineer most accurately compare modern SMR designs to the Chernobyl-era reactor?": "",
  "Modern SMRs are identical in design to the Chernobyl reactor, particularly regarding flaws in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "Modern SMRs incorporate passive safety features that use natural forces like gravity and convection to cool the reactor without human intervention or external power, making a Chernobyl-type accident essentially impossible": "",
  "All nuclear reactors have identical safety profiles regardless of design based on established principles": "",
  "Modern reactors are less safe than Chernobyl because they use more fuel based on the prevailing evidence": "",
  "Modern small modular reactors incorporate passive safety systems that rely on natural physical phenomena such as gravity, natural convection, and compressed gas to shut down and cool the reactor without human intervention or external electrical power. The Chernobyl reactor had fundamental design flaws, including a positive void coefficient and lack of a containment structure, that are not present in modern designs.": "",
  "France generates approximately 70% of its electricity from nuclear power and has some of the lowest electricity-related carbon emissions in Europe. Meanwhile, a neighboring country with similar energy demand relies primarily on coal and has much higher emissions. What does this comparison demonstrate about nuclear energy's role in addressing climate change?": "",
  "France's low emissions are entirely due to renewable energy, not nuclear": "",
  "Nuclear power can serve as a large-scale, low-carbon electricity source that significantly reduces a nation's greenhouse gas emissions compared to fossil fuel dependence": "",
  "Coal-dependent countries always have lower emissions than nuclear-powered ones": "",
  "Nuclear power has no relationship to carbon emissions": "",
  "France's experience demonstrates that nuclear power can provide large-scale, reliable, low-carbon electricity. By generating most of its power from nuclear rather than fossil fuels, France achieves significantly lower electricity-related CO2 emissions than countries relying on coal. This makes nuclear energy a potentially important tool in combating climate change.": "",
  "A nuclear power plant operator notices that the reactor's power output is decreasing over time even though no control rods have been adjusted. An engineer explains that some of the fission products are absorbing neutrons and reducing reactor efficiency. What term describes this phenomenon, and what is the typical solution?": "",
  "Reactor meltdown; the solution is to evacuate the area": "",
  "Thermal runaway; the solution is to add more coolant": "",
  "Fuel enrichment failure; the solution is to add more uranium-238": "",
  "Neutron poisoning; the solution involves adjusting control rods or waiting for the absorbing isotopes to decay": "",
  "Neutron poisoning (also called xenon poisoning) occurs when fission products, particularly xenon-135, accumulate in the reactor core and absorb neutrons, reducing reactor reactivity and power output. Operators can compensate by partially withdrawing control rods or waiting for the xenon to decay naturally, which has a half-life of about 9 hours.": "",
  "A government is debating whether to invest billions of dollars in a fusion research program. Critics argue the money should go toward proven technologies like solar and wind. A fusion scientist presents their case to lawmakers. Which of the following is the strongest argument for continued fusion research?": "",
  "Fusion produces no radiation of any kind": "",
  "Fusion is already cheaper than solar and wind energy": "",
  "Fusion could provide virtually limitless, clean energy using abundant fuel from seawater, with minimal long-lived radioactive waste compared to fission": "",
  "Fusion reactors have been commercially operating for decades": "",
  "The strongest argument for fusion research is its transformative potential: fusion fuel (deuterium from seawater and tritium bred from lithium) is virtually inexhaustible, the reaction produces no greenhouse gases, and the radioactive waste from fusion is far less long-lived than fission waste. If achieved, fusion could provide clean baseload energy for centuries.": "",
  "A medical isotope laboratory uses a small nuclear reactor to produce technetium-99m, which is used in millions of diagnostic imaging procedures worldwide each year. The reactor is scheduled for maintenance, and hospitals fear a shortage of the isotope. What does this scenario reveal about nuclear technology beyond electricity generation?": "",
  "Nuclear technology has critical applications in medicine, including producing radioactive isotopes used in diagnostic imaging and cancer treatment": "",
  "Hospitals can easily produce their own nuclear isotopes without reactors": "",
  "Nuclear reactors are only used for making weapons": "",
  "Medical isotopes are only used in experimental treatments": "",
  "Nuclear reactors have important applications beyond electricity generation, including the production of medical isotopes. Technetium-99m is the most widely used medical radioisotope, employed in approximately 40 million diagnostic procedures annually worldwide. This demonstrates the broader societal value of nuclear technology in healthcare.": "",
  "A coastal city is considering building a new nuclear power plant to replace an aging coal plant. During a public hearing, a citizen asks about the risk of a tsunami damaging the plant, referencing the 2011 Fukushima disaster. What design lesson from Fukushima would most directly address this concern?": "",
  "Using the exact same design as the Fukushima plant since it eventually was controlled": "",
  "Building the plant inland rather than on the coast, if feasible, or elevating critical safety systems well above maximum projected flood levels": "",
  "Placing the backup generators in the basement for protection": "",
  "Not building any safety systems since natural disasters cannot be predicted": "",
  "The Fukushima disaster was caused by a tsunami that flooded the backup diesel generators located in the basement, leading to a total loss of cooling. The key lesson is to either site plants away from tsunami zones or ensure that all critical safety systems, especially backup power, are elevated well above maximum projected flood levels. Many post-Fukushima safety upgrades focus on flood protection.": "",
  "A physics student calculates that 1 kilogram of uranium-235 undergoing complete fission releases approximately the same energy as burning 2,700 metric tons of coal. The student is surprised by this enormous difference. What fundamental principle explains why nuclear reactions release so much more energy than chemical reactions like combustion?": "",
  "Coal absorbs energy during combustion while uranium releases it, particularly regarding enormous when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "Nuclear reactions involve more atoms than chemical reactions, particularly regarding small as predicted by standard models": "",
  "Einstein's mass-energy equivalence (E = mc2) shows that nuclear reactions convert a small amount of mass directly into an enormous amount of energy, while chemical reactions involve only rearrangement of electrons": "",
  "Uranium atoms are physically larger than carbon atoms, so they contain more energy under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "Einstein's famous equation E = mc2 explains why nuclear reactions release millions of times more energy per kilogram than chemical reactions. In fission, a tiny fraction of the uranium's mass is converted directly into energy. Because the speed of light (c) is enormous, even a small mass loss produces a tremendous amount of energy. Chemical reactions only rearrange electrons between atoms without any mass conversion.": ""
}